enna, Turin, and Naples, drawing on rare archival materials to show how ideas central to the emergence of secular democracy touched all facets of daily life. Human frailties once attributed to sin were now viewed through the lens of the newly conceived social sciences. People entered churches not to pray but to admire the architecture, and spent their Sunday mornings reading a newspaper or even a risqué book. The secular-minded pursued their own temporal and commercial well-being without concern for the life hereafter, regarding their successes as the rewards for their actions, their failures as the result of blind economic forces.A majestic work of intellectual and cultural history, The Secular Enlightenment demonstrates how secular values and pursuits took hold of eighteenth-century Europe, spilled into the American colonies, and left their lasting imprint on the Western world for generations to come.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aEnlightenment. 0aSecularismzEuropexHistoryy18th century. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh  aAmericas.  aCelestino Galiani.  aChristian theology.  aChristian time.  aChristianity.  aEdinburgh.  aEnlightenment.  aFrench Enlightenment.  aGerman Enlightenment.  aGerman universities.  aInquisition.  aItalian Enlightenment.  aItalian intellectual circles.  aLeibniz.  aLocke.  aMilan.  aNaples.  aNapoleon.  aNewtonian optics.  aRomantics.  aRousseau.  aScotland.  aScottish Enlightenment.  aSecular Enlightenment.  aVoltaire.  aWestphalia.  aabsolutism.  aanti-Catholic.  aanticlerical.  aatheism.  acalendar.  acensorship.  aclocks.  acommerce.  aeducated elite.  aeducated people.  aeighteenth-century philosophes.  aenlightened attitudes.  aenlightened ideas.  aenlightened people.  aenlightened thinking.  ae